    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, I apologize for the confusion! The goblin was just a metaphor for the stuck motor, but I see you need the technical details.\n\nThe actual part that is likely broken is the **start capacitor** or the **run capacitor**. These small cylindrical components store electrical energy to give the motor a \"kick\" to start spinning. If the capacitor fails, the motor gets stuck in a magnetic field, humming loudly but never turning. It's like a key that is stuck in the ignition; the engine makes a noise trying to start, but the car won't move.\n\nAnother possibility is a **seized bearing** inside the motor or a **blown fuse** on the contactor. If the bearing is worn out, the fan blades can't rotate freely, creating that friction noise.\n\n**Is it safe to go out there?**\n**No, it is not safe.** Even though the unit isn't currently arcing, the capacitor can still hold a lethal charge of electricity for a long time after the power is turned off. Touching it could give you a severe shock. You should **not** touch the unit yourself. Instead, turn off the circuit breaker for that specific AC unit at your main panel, wait a",
